[SPEAKER_07]: Does anybody want to ask Kit if she knows a good way to?

1121
01:41:33,076 --> 01:41:34,257
[SPEAKER_07]: I can do that.

1122
01:41:34,918 --> 01:41:35,479
[SPEAKER_07]: OK.

1123
01:41:35,499 --> 01:41:42,905
[SPEAKER_07]: Danielle's going to ask Kit if there's a way that we can send out the link to that population.

1124
01:41:43,725 --> 01:41:47,627
[SPEAKER_09]: Has anyone asked the churches?

1125
01:41:48,348 --> 01:41:52,670
[SPEAKER_07]: In terms, ask them if they would send it out, send out the link.

1126
01:41:52,931 --> 01:41:54,271
[SPEAKER_09]: Leave them at the back of the church?

1127
01:41:55,912 --> 01:41:56,373
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah.

1128
01:41:56,533 --> 01:42:11,522
[SPEAKER_05]: I tried to contact the churches about our October public meeting and sent out an email to every email that I could find for any house of worship.

1129
01:42:12,747 --> 01:42:17,591
[SPEAKER_05]: Asking them to promote our October public meeting.

1130
01:42:17,651 --> 01:42:28,320
[SPEAKER_05]: Now, I don't go to these places, so I don't know if they did mention it or didn't, but I didn't get one single response back saying, oh, great idea.

1131
01:42:28,360 --> 01:42:29,982
[SPEAKER_05]: I'm happy to do that or anything.

1132
01:42:30,302 --> 01:42:32,904
[SPEAKER_05]: I don't know what happened.

1133
01:42:36,110 --> 01:42:37,471
[SPEAKER_07]: So we have an option here.

1134
01:42:37,551 --> 01:42:41,914
[SPEAKER_07]: We can try to assign some people to do outreach on this survey.

1135
01:42:41,974 --> 01:42:49,500
[SPEAKER_07]: We can all individually commit to sending it out to whatever channels we are a part of.

1136
01:42:49,520 --> 01:42:51,582
[SPEAKER_07]: I mean, I know everybody is busy.

1137
01:42:55,845 --> 01:42:59,007
[SPEAKER_07]: You know, adding more tasks on at this point might be hard.

1138
01:42:59,287 --> 01:43:03,890
[SPEAKER_07]: We are getting, you know, the city is putting it out through their channels.

1139
01:43:04,010 --> 01:43:07,873
[SPEAKER_07]: So it's not like, you know, it's not like it's not reaching anybody.

1140
01:43:10,154 --> 01:43:21,662
[SPEAKER_07]: What do people think about how much work we wanna do on trying to, you know, get this thing to- I have a suggestion.

1141
01:43:22,122 --> 01:43:22,282
[SPEAKER_03]: Okay.

1142
01:43:24,096 --> 01:43:42,941
[SPEAKER_03]: if we just keep blasting it everywhere for the next month or two, but to really then organize something maybe on election day, where we would be at every polling place and ask people as they were coming out to fill out a survey.

1143
01:43:42,961 --> 01:43:47,542
[SPEAKER_07]: Yeah, we have to be a number of feet away, right, I think, legally.

1144
01:43:48,988 --> 01:43:51,569
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah, no, we won't be campaigning, we won't be campaigning, we're not campaigning.

1145
01:43:51,589 --> 01:43:53,811
[SPEAKER_09]: Yeah, we won't be campaigning, that's true, that's true.

1146
01:43:53,831 --> 01:43:55,011
[SPEAKER_09]: We're not campaigning, so.

1147
01:43:55,431 --> 01:43:58,693
[SPEAKER_09]: But I would still check to see if that's allowed at polling places.

1148
01:44:01,875 --> 01:44:17,143
[SPEAKER_08]: There are regulations about how far away you stand and whatever, but I actually was thinking along the same way, because that's the one time when at least people who are voting, we could approach and say, are you aware of

1149
01:44:19,503 --> 01:44:26,407
[SPEAKER_08]: Um, you know, and here's if we could put together a card with the website so that they could respond to give those out.

1150
01:44:26,467 --> 01:44:30,028
[SPEAKER_08]: I think that would be effective.

1151
01:44:30,489 --> 01:44:31,629
[SPEAKER_07]: We have a QR code.

1152
01:44:32,330 --> 01:44:32,890
[SPEAKER_07]: Um, yeah.

1153
01:44:33,010 --> 01:44:38,553
[SPEAKER_07]: So let's, um, let's put it on the agenda for the next meeting to talk about that.

1154
01:44:38,613 --> 01:44:42,215
[SPEAKER_07]: At the very least, we can make sure that we have signs with a QR code.

1155
01:44:44,115 --> 01:44:44,436
[SPEAKER_07]: Okay.

1156
01:44:44,996 --> 01:44:45,296
[SPEAKER_07]: Awesome.

1157
01:44:46,857 --> 01:44:48,598
[SPEAKER_07]: Um, okay.

1158
01:44:49,687 --> 01:44:59,550
[SPEAKER_07]: Um, you know, we don't technically have 10 more minutes and I apologize because I don't know, maybe it's because I'm out of town.

1159
01:44:59,570 --> 01:45:08,193
[SPEAKER_07]: I feel like I let this meeting get away and we haven't gotten to deliberating about should Medford's charter have a preamble and I don't want to give that short shrift.

1160
01:45:08,293 --> 01:45:13,294
[SPEAKER_07]: So I think I'm going to move that we table it until the next meeting.

1161
01:45:15,295 --> 01:45:15,475
[SPEAKER_07]: Okay.

1162
01:45:18,122 --> 01:45:20,724
[SPEAKER_07]: Does anybody want to second that motion?

1163
01:45:21,544 --> 01:45:23,405
[SPEAKER_09]: I'll second that motion.

1164
01:45:23,985 --> 01:45:24,645
[SPEAKER_07]: All in favor?

1165
01:45:24,665 --> 01:45:25,285
[SPEAKER_07]: Aye.

1166
01:45:27,106 --> 01:45:28,447
[SPEAKER_09]: Melva, can I say something?

1167
01:45:29,047 --> 01:45:31,268
[SPEAKER_07]: Yeah, and then I know Francis wants to speak.

1168
01:45:31,288 --> 01:45:31,948
[SPEAKER_09]: Just about this.

1169
01:45:32,548 --> 01:45:34,489
[SPEAKER_09]: I cannot be at the October 5th meeting.

1170
01:45:35,290 --> 01:45:35,610
[SPEAKER_09]: Okay.

1171
01:45:35,770 --> 01:45:43,453
[SPEAKER_09]: But I want to know if I can go on record today as saying after having read all of the preambles and thought about this quite a bit before this meeting tonight,

1172
01:45:44,077 --> 01:45:45,980
[SPEAKER_09]: I would be in favor of a preamble.

1173
01:45:46,000 --> 01:45:53,432
[SPEAKER_09]: I don't know if that counts, but I just want to go on record to say that I think a preamble would be pretty powerful and pretty important.

1174
01:45:53,973 --> 01:45:54,413
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

1175
01:45:56,557 --> 01:45:58,520
[SPEAKER_07]: Okay, Francis.

1176
01:46:01,696 --> 01:46:06,779
[SPEAKER_00]: I just wanted to remind you that you have that what is a charter flyer that's at a glance.

1177
01:46:06,899 --> 01:46:12,382
[SPEAKER_00]: It's short, it's simple, it's translated, and it has the QR code if I'm not mistaken.

1178
01:46:13,022 --> 01:46:17,245
[SPEAKER_00]: So, you know, try to avoid reinventing the wheel and use what

1179
01:46:18,345 --> 01:46:18,686
[SPEAKER_00]: have.

1180
01:46:19,186 --> 01:46:21,747
[SPEAKER_00]: And also the non-traditional routes, right?

1181
01:46:22,407 --> 01:46:28,209
[SPEAKER_00]: Does anybody know that on Saturday at the Andrews School they're celebrating Brazilian Flag Day?

1182
01:46:28,269 --> 01:46:33,932
[SPEAKER_00]: You've had the surveys, the flyer, the glossary, all these things have already been translated.

1183
01:46:34,432 --> 01:46:39,554
[SPEAKER_00]: So those materials are available and should be used.

1184
01:46:42,215 --> 01:46:44,256
[SPEAKER_07]: Is anybody planning to go to Brazilian Flag Day?

1185
01:46:44,276 --> 01:46:45,236
[SPEAKER_07]: I am

1186
01:46:47,742 --> 01:46:49,483
[SPEAKER_07]: going to be in the car all day.

1187
01:46:49,683 --> 01:46:51,184
[SPEAKER_07]: So I know I'm not.

1188
01:46:54,206 --> 01:46:56,947
[SPEAKER_07]: Because that would be a great opportunity to redo.

1189
01:46:56,987 --> 01:46:58,548
[SPEAKER_07]: We have glossaries.

1190
01:46:58,708 --> 01:47:00,569
[SPEAKER_07]: We have translated materials.

1191
01:47:05,272 --> 01:47:05,592
[SPEAKER_07]: OK.

1192
01:47:06,112 --> 01:47:12,195
[SPEAKER_07]: So in terms of events, that's the next on the agenda.

1193
01:47:12,416 --> 01:47:16,738
[SPEAKER_07]: Ice Cream Social, does anybody, I mean, I thought it was very successful.

1194
01:47:18,970 --> 01:47:20,591
[SPEAKER_07]: We talked to a lot of people.

1195
01:47:20,611 --> 01:47:24,273
[SPEAKER_07]: That was when we sort of brought out the survey.

1196
